<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="55" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,337,151,177]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[345,656,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Macrostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occidentalis">
<emphasis box="[345,656,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Macrostomus occidentalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears most closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[1040,1209,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Macrostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvithorax">
<emphasis box="[1040,1209,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">M. fulvithorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the basis of the truncate male tergite 8 projection, the bifid posterior lobe of the male cercus and the hypandrium without ventral setae. It differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[496,668,229,254]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Macrostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvithorax">
<emphasis box="[496,668,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">M. fulvithorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a more acute apical protuberance on the hypandrium and a less sclerotized ventral surface of the hypandrium.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,511,306,332]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Biogeographical pattern.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Amorim &amp; Pires" box="[685,974,306,332]" firstAuthor="Amorim" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" pagination="183 - 219" refId="ref8890" refString="Amorim, D. S. &amp; Pires, M. R. S. (1996) Neotropical biogeography and a method for maximum biodiversity estimation, In: Bicudo, C. E. M. &amp; Menezes, N. A. (Eds.). Biodiversity in Brazil, a first approach. CNPq, Sao Paulo, pp. 183 - 219." type="book chapter" year="1996">Amorim &amp; Pires (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Amorim &amp; Silva" box="[988,1275,306,332]" firstAuthor="Amorim" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" pagination="177 - 200" refId="ref8959" refString="Amorim, D. S. &amp; Silva, V. C. (2002) How far advanced was Diptera evolution in the Pangaea? Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (n. s.) 38, 177 - 200." type="journal article" year="2002">Amorim &amp; Silva (2002)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Amorim" firstAuthor="Amorim" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" pagination="71 - 97" refId="ref8831" refString="Amorim, D. S. (2009) Neotropical Diptera Diversity: Richness, Patterns, and Perspectives. In: Pape, T., Bickel, D. &amp; Meier, R. (Eds), Diptera Diversity: Status, Challenges and Tools. Brill, Leiden, pp. 71 - 97." type="book chapter" year="2009">Amorim (2009)</bibRefCitation>
the continental northern Neotropical region is divided in two components. The NW Neotropical component is northwest of the Amazonas-Madeira-Mamoré Rivers and extends as far as tropical 
<collectingCountry box="[1287,1380,384,410]" name="Mexico" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. The other component is southeast of these rivers, called the SE Neotropical component. The NW Neotropical component is further subdivided into the transandean area, Chocó-Central America (Chocó-CA), and the Northwest Amazonia (NWAm) area. The NWAm is further subdivided into the North Amazonia (NAm) and the Southwest Amazonia (SWAm) (
<figureCitation box="[590,666,538,564]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1846,1870]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,894,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-311@14.[151,1436,893,1821]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 7. General biogeographic pattern of the northern Neotropical region based on different groups of vertebrates, insects and plants (After Amorim 2009)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321592" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321592/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). The NAm area runs from Japurá-Caquetá Rivers to the coast (Atlantic Ocean) with its eastern and southern limits extending along the Parnaiba River, between the states of Maranhão and Piauí, to the south several hundred kilometres and west crossing the Tocantins River to the Xingu River, before running north to the Amazon River. The SWAm area includes a portion south of the Caquetá-Japurá rivers, as well as west of the Madeira River and south along the Mamoré River to 
<collectingCountry box="[1300,1386,693,719]" name="Bolivia" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[151,209,732,758]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Peru</collectingCountry>
. The SE Neotropical component is also subdivided in two areas: the Southeast Amazonia (SEAm) and the Atlantic Forest (
<figureCitation box="[388,461,770,796]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1846,1870]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,894,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-311@14.[151,1436,893,1821]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 7. General biogeographic pattern of the northern Neotropical region based on different groups of vertebrates, insects and plants (After Amorim 2009)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321592" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321592/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). The relationships of these regions to one another have been presented in an area cladogram (
<figureCitation box="[290,360,809,835]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="14.[151,254,1846,1870]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,894,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-311@14.[151,1436,893,1821]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 7. General biogeographic pattern of the northern Neotropical region based on different groups of vertebrates, insects and plants (After Amorim 2009)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5321592" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5321592/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Amorim" box="[414,602,809,835]" firstAuthor="Amorim" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" pagination="71 - 97" refId="ref8831" refString="Amorim, D. S. (2009) Neotropical Diptera Diversity: Richness, Patterns, and Perspectives. In: Pape, T., Bickel, D. &amp; Meier, R. (Eds), Diptera Diversity: Status, Challenges and Tools. Brill, Leiden, pp. 71 - 97." type="book chapter" year="2009">Amorim (2009)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
